    "response_text": "Certainly! When explaining compound interest, it's important to balance clarity with depth. I'll start with an intuitive explanation and then provide a formula for those who prefer a more mathematical approach.\n\n### Intuitive Explanation\n\nImagine you have $100 in a savings account that earns 5% interest annually. At the end of the first year, you would earn $5 in interest (5% of $100), bringing your total to $105. Now, here’s where compound interest gets interesting: instead of just earning interest on your original $100, you earn interest on the new total of $105. \n\nIn the second year, you earn 5% interest on $105, which is $5.25. So, at the end of the second year, your total grows to $110.25. This process continues, with each year's interest being calculated on the new total, leading to exponential growth over time",
